ns with the basics, explaining how to develop a professional style, get started on a piece of writing, create a first draft, and edit it into a strong final product. She then offers practical advice on more than a dozen forms of writing, from emails and slide decks to proposals and cover letters. Along the way, Coven provides a wealth of concrete examples and simple templates that make the concepts easy to understand and apply.Based on Coven’s popular writing classes and workshops at Princeton University as well as her decades of experience in the public and private sectors, Writing on the Job addresses the real challenges professionals face in today’s digital age, and shares essential practices that can improve the performance of any organization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBusiness communication. 0aBusiness writing. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Style Manuals.2bisacsh  aAbbreviation (music).  aAdvertising.  aApostrophe.  aAudience analysis.  aAuthor.  aAutofill.  aBusiness case.  aBusiness letter.  aCalculation.  aCallout.  aClassroom.  aContraction (grammar).  aCorporate jargon.  aCover letter.  aCreative writing.  aCriticism.  aCustomer.  aData visualization.  aEditing.  aEditorial.  aElevator pitch.  aEmail.  aEmailing.  aEmployment.  aExecutive summary.  aHeadline.  aJargon.  aJob description.  aJournalist.  aLead paragraph.  aLecture.  aLynne Truss.  aManuscript.  aNewspaper.  aNote (typography).  aNote-taking.  aOp-ed.  aParagraph.  aParenthesis (rhetoric).  aPhrase.  aPlatitude.  aPress release.  aProcrastination.  aProduct design.  aProductivity software.  aProofreading.  aPublic speaking.  aPunctuation.  aQuotation mark.  aReading (process).  aRepetition (rhetorical device).  aRequest for propos